  "summary": "The LLM completions request lifecycle spans two services — the Sourcegraph frontend and Cody Gateway — with rate limiting enforced at multiple layers.\n\n**Layer 1 — GraphQL Entry Point (Frontend)**\nThe `Completions` GraphQL mutation is defined in `cmd/frontend/graphqlbackend/completions.go` and implemented by `completionsResolver` in `cmd/frontend/internal/completions/resolvers/resolver.go`. On entry it: (1) calls `completionsapis.IsEnabled` (which delegates to `cody.IsCodyEnabled`) to check if the feature is enabled; (2) resolves the default chat/fast-chat model via `modelconfig.Get()`; (3) checks the per-user Redis-backed rate limit via `rateLimiter.TryAcquire`; then (4) calls `client.Get()` → `client.Complete()` to produce the completion.\n\n**Layer 2 — HTTP API Handlers (Frontend)**\nFor HTTP Cody API clients (VS Code, JetBrains), requests hit `/.api/completions/stream` (chat) or `/.api/completions/code`, handled by `CompletionsHandler.ServeHTTP` in `cmd/frontend/internal/httpapi/completions/handler.go`. The handler enforces: (a) completions-enabled check; (b) client version/CodyIgnore compatibility guard; (c) model resolution and capability validation (vision, tools); (d) another Redis-backed per-user/per-IP rate limiter via `h.rl.TryAcquire` using `limiter.go`. The rate limiter reads a per-user daily quota override from the database (`db.Users().GetChatCompletionsQuota`) or falls back to the global `completions.perUserDailyLimit` site config. Exceeded limits produce 429 responses with `x-ratelimit-limit`, `x-ratelimit-remaining`, and `retry-after` headers.\n\n**Layer 3 — Provider Selection (Frontend Client)**\n`internal/completions/client/client.go:getAPIProvider` inspects `provider.ServerSideConfig` to pick the correct backend client: AWSBedrock, AzureOpenAI, OpenAICompatible, Anthropic (direct), Google (direct), GenericProvider (Fireworks or OpenAI direct), or SourcegraphProvider (Cody Gateway). When the provider is `SourcegraphProvider`, `codygateway.NewClient` is instantiated, which builds a `gatewayDoer` that injects auth headers (via `auther.Authenticate`) and sets the `X-Sourcegraph-Feature` and `X-Sourcegraph-Scope` headers before proxying the request to Cody Gateway.\n\n**Layer 4 — Cody Gateway Auth (Middleware)**\nAt Cody Gateway, the `registerStandardEndpoint` wrapper in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/httpapi/handler.go` stacks: latency → interaction-tracking → instrumentation → `authr.Middleware` → request-logger → handler. `auth.Authenticator.Middleware` (in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/auth/auth.go`) calls `Sources.Get(ctx, r.Header)` to resolve the caller into a Gateway `Actor` by trying each registered actor source (enterprise subscriptions, workspaces, dotcom users). Failures produce 401 (credentials denied/unrecognized), 403 (actor forbidden/access disabled), or 503 (upstream error). A successful auth stores the `Actor` in context.\n\n**Layer 5 — Cody Gateway Feature Rate Limiting**\n`featurelimiter.Handle` (in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/httpapi/featurelimiter/featurelimiter.go`) extracts the feature from the `X-Sourcegraph-Feature` header, then calls `act.Limiter(ctx, logger, cache, feature, rateLimitNotifier)` to get the actor's per-feature Redis limiter, followed by `l.TryAcquire`. Rate limits are stored on the actor (`Actor.RateLimits map[Feature]RateLimit`) and come from the actor source (e.g. the enterprise subscription's configured limits). Exceeding the limit fires a `rate_limited` event log and returns 429 with `retry-after`. This is the layer most likely to produce 429s for legitimate but high-volume customers.\n\n**Layer 6 — Upstream Handler (Cody Gateway → LLM Provider)**\n`makeUpstreamHandler` in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/httpapi/completions/upstream.go` performs: request body parsing → abuse/flagging check (`shouldFlagRequest`) → model allowlist validation (`isAllowedModel` against embedded model config) → model availability circuit-breaker (`modelAvailabilityTracker`) → request transformation and proxying to the upstream LLM API. If the upstream itself returns 429, it is rewritten to 503 (to prevent clients from naively retrying) and a `retry-after` header is forwarded or defaulted. Provider-specific handlers (Anthropic, Fireworks, OpenAI, Google) live in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/httpapi/completions/` and each implement `upstreamHandlerMethods`.\n\n**429 Root Causes Summary**\n1. Frontend per-user daily rate limit exceeded (Redis counter in `limiter.go`) → 429 with `rate_limit_exceeded` JSON error code.\n2. Cody Gateway actor feature rate limit exceeded (`featurelimiter.HandleFeature`) → 429 from Gateway.\n3. Upstream LLM provider rate limit (TPM/RPM quota exhausted) → rewritten by Gateway to 503 with `retry-after`; clients may misinterpret this as a 429 if they observe the original upstream headers."
}

