  "summary": "The LLM completions request lifecycle spans two services — the Sourcegraph frontend and Cody Gateway — with rate limiting enforced at multiple layers.\n\n**Layer 1 — GraphQL Entry Point (Frontend)**\nThe `Completions` GraphQL mutation is defined in `cmd/frontend/graphqlbackend/completions.go` and implemented by `completionsResolver` in `cmd/frontend/internal/completions/resolvers/resolver.go`. On entry it: (1) calls `completionsapis.IsEnabled` (which delegates to `cody.IsCodyEnabled`) to check if the feature is enabled; (2) resolves the default chat/fast-chat model via `modelconfig.Get()`; (3) checks the per-user Redis-backed rate limit via `rateLimiter.TryAcquire`; then (4) calls `client.Get()` -> `client.Complete()` to produce the completion.\n\n**Layer 2 — HTTP API Handlers (Frontend)**\nFor HTTP Cody API clients (VS Code, JetBrains), requests hit `/.api/completions/stream` (chat) or `/.api/completions/code`, handled by `CompletionsHandler.ServeHTTP` in `cmd/frontend/internal/httpapi/completions/handler.go`. The handler enforces: (a) completions-enabled check via `checkCompletionsEnabled`; (b) client version / CodyIgnore compatibility guard via `checkClientCodyIgnoreCompatibility`; (c) model resolution and capability validation (vision, tools) via `validateRequestCapabilities`; (d) a Redis-backed per-user/per-IP rate limiter via `h.rl.TryAcquire` (in `limiter.go`). The rate limiter reads a per-user daily quota override from the database (`db.Users().GetChatCompletionsQuota`) or falls back to the global `completions.perUserDailyLimit` site config. Exceeded limits produce HTTP 429 responses with `x-ratelimit-limit`, `x-ratelimit-remaining`, and `retry-after` headers.\n\n**Layer 3 — Provider Selection (Frontend Client)**\n`internal/completions/client/client.go:getAPIProvider` inspects `provider.ServerSideConfig` to pick the correct backend client among 7 options: AWSBedrock, AzureOpenAI, OpenAICompatible, Anthropic (direct), Google (direct), GenericProvider (Fireworks or OpenAI direct), or SourcegraphProvider (Cody Gateway). When the provider is `SourcegraphProvider`, `codygateway.NewClient` is instantiated, which builds a `gatewayDoer` that injects authentication headers (via `auther.Authenticate`), sets the `X-Sourcegraph-Feature` and `X-Sourcegraph-Scope` headers, and proxies the request to Cody Gateway.\n\n**Layer 4 — Cody Gateway Auth (Middleware)**\nAt Cody Gateway, `registerStandardEndpoint` in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/httpapi/handler.go` stacks middleware: latency -> interaction-tracking -> instrumentation -> `authr.Middleware` -> request-logger -> handler. `auth.Authenticator.Middleware` (in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/auth/auth.go`) calls `Sources.Get(ctx, r.Header)` to resolve the caller into a Gateway `Actor` by trying each registered source (enterprise subscriptions, workspaces, dotcom users). Failures produce 401 (credentials denied/unrecognized), 403 (actor forbidden/access disabled), or 503 (upstream error). Success stores the `Actor` in context.\n\n**Layer 5 — Cody Gateway Feature Rate Limiting**\n`featurelimiter.Handle` in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/httpapi/featurelimiter/featurelimiter.go` extracts the feature from the `X-Sourcegraph-Feature` header, then calls `act.Limiter(ctx, logger, cache, feature, rateLimitNotifier)` to get the actor's per-feature Redis limiter, followed by `l.TryAcquire`. Rate limits are stored on the actor (`Actor.RateLimits map[Feature]RateLimit`) and sourced from the actor's enterprise subscription configuration. Exceeding the limit fires a `rate_limited` event log and returns HTTP 429 with a `retry-after` header. This is the layer most likely to produce intermittent 429s for legitimate high-volume customers.\n\n**Layer 6 — Upstream Handler (Cody Gateway -> LLM Provider)**\n`makeUpstreamHandler` in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/httpapi/completions/upstream.go` performs: request body parsing -> abuse/flagging check (`shouldFlagRequest`) -> model allowlist validation (`isAllowedModel` against embedded model config) -> model availability circuit-breaker (`modelAvailabilityTracker`, which blocks requests to models with recent 429s or timeouts) -> request transformation and proxying to the upstream LLM API. If the upstream itself returns 429, it is rewritten to 503 (to prevent clients from naively retrying) and a `retry-after` header is forwarded or defaulted to 30 seconds. Provider-specific handlers (Anthropic, Fireworks, OpenAI, Google) live in `cmd/cody-gateway/internal/httpapi/completions/` and each implement the `upstreamHandlerMethods` interface.\n\n**429 Root Causes Summary**\n1. Frontend per-user daily quota exceeded (Redis counter in `limiter.go`, checked in `ProcessCompletion`) -> HTTP 429 with JSON error code `rate_limit_exceeded`.\n2. Cody Gateway actor feature rate limit exceeded (`featurelimiter.HandleFeature`) -> HTTP 429 from Gateway before the request reaches the LLM.\n3. Upstream LLM provider quota exhausted (TPM/RPM limit) -> Gateway rewrites upstream 429 to HTTP 503 with `retry-after`; the `modelAvailabilityTracker` also blocks subsequent requests to that model temporarily."
}
